 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
August 4, 1994, Thursday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 10; Column 4; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
99 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
BASEBALL STRIKE PLANS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * I agree with your editorial "Doesn't Anyone Care About the Fans? (July 
30)."After the last (baseball) strike I ceased spending my money to help pay 
salaries and club expenses. Instead, I have saved it for trips and cruises. 
Believe it or not, it doesn't take very many bypassed games to enjoy something 
far more enjoyable. 
</P>
<P>
 It also gripes me when I hear someone object to a doctor making $100,000 after 
15 years of school. 
</P>
<P>
 What is the average salary of a baseball player? Could it be $1.5 million for 
playing a game that in the end really means nothing? 
</P>
<P>
 CHARLES O. GASKINS 
</P>
<P>
 Anaheim 
</P>
