<HEADLINE>
<P>
TOPICS / BRIEFLY; RECREATION: GOLF PROGRAM ALSO OFFERS ACADEMIC AID 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 In a new program offered by two golf associations, inner-city youths in Los 
Angeles can learn to play golf and also meet career and college counselors. 
</P>
<P>
 The Junior Golf Program, a joint project that the American Golf Corp. and the 
Western States Golf Assn. recently launched in Los Angeles, offers minority 
youths free lessons from professional golfers, career development assistance 
and college scholarships. 
</P>
<P>
 Since the nationwide program was launched in 1987, more than 5,000 inner-city 
youths have learned to play golf, according to American Golf spokesman Kevin 
Roberts. 
</P>
<P>
 "In addition to providing these children with a healthy and fun activity, golf 
provides them with a number of positive social skills including 
self-discipline, self-control and commitment," said Roberts.  
</P>
<P>
 Similar programs exist in New York, Virginia, Florida and Arizona. 
</P>
