<HEADLINE>
<P>
DO IT!: UJENA 5,000 PROMISES TO BE A MODEL RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICK VANDERKNYFF, Rick VanderKnyff is a member of The Times Orange County 
Edition staff. 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 On hand Sunday morning for the running of the Ujena 5,000 in Dana Point will 
be KNBC, "Entertainment Tonight" and probably an army of still photographers. 
ESPN will also be there, filming for a planned half-hour special. 
</P>
<P>
 Speed isn't the media draw; no one is expecting this field to break any 
records. The attention-getter is a group of more than 200 women sports models 
who are running the 5K race as part of a series of events, the prize being a 
chance to be on the cover of Swimwear Illustrated. 
</P>
<P>
 A first-time event, the Ujena 5,000 is the only part of the competition that's 
open to public participation, and organizers are hoping for a large field with 
more than just models. 
</P>
<P>
 The run starts at Salt Creek Beach, next to the Ritz-Carlton Hotel, and 
promises scenic views of the Pacific as it skirts the Links at Monarch Beach 
and finishes on a park-like bluff overlooking the water. 
</P>
<P>
 There will be separate start times for men and women, not because of the 
presence of the models but "mainly because of the course constraints," said 
Scott Muirhead of Dana Point-based Race Pace Promotions, organizers of the run. 
Breaking up the field by gender has been an increasingly popular way of cutting 
down on crowding. 
</P>
<P>
 For the models, other events include a volleyball tournament, an aerobics 
contest and a swimsuit competition. The top 10 finishers will then duel in a 
"power aerobics" contest for cover-photo privileges. 
</P>
<P>
 "The main thing that we're trying to do is tell people that models (aren't) 
just bimbos," said Bob Anderson, founder and publisher of the Sunnyvale-based 
magazine. "Models take care of themselves, and some of them can put in a pretty 
decent time in the 5K." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 Runners who can live without putting that claim to the test have another 
seaside run they can opt for Sunday morning. The seventh annual Fiesta 5000 in 
San Clemente kicks off a one-day street festival that will include 
entertainment, food and games. 
</P>
<P>
 Registration starts at 6 a.m., and the 5K run/walk begins at 8 a.m. Entry is 
$20, including T-shirt. Information: (714) 492-1131. 
</P>
<P>
 * What: Ujena 5,000 running race. 
</P>
<P>
 * When: Sunday, Aug. 7, 8 a.m. men's race, 9 a.m. women's race. Registration 
opens at 6:30 a.m. 
</P>
<P>
 * Where: Salt Creek Beach, Dana Point. 
</P>
<P>
 * Whereabouts: From the San Diego (405) Freeway, exit at Crown Valley Parkway 
and go south to Pacific Coast Highway, then turn left. Salt Creek Beach will be 
on the right. 
</P>
<P>
 * Wherewithal: $20, including T-shirt. 
</P>
<P>
 * Where to call: (714) 661-6547. 
</P>
</TEXT>
