<HEADLINE>
<P>
WEST VENTURA COUNTY FOCUS: VENTURA; STUDENTS WILL EXHIBIT PHOTOS FROM CUBA TRIP 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIGUEL BUSTILLO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A group of Ventura College photography students who recently returned from a 
trip to Cuba brought back images of the island's vibrant people that will soon 
become the focus of an upcoming show at the college gallery. 
</P>
<P>
 Ten students and Ventura photographers visited the Communist-ruled island in 
June with a contingent of architectural history students from Virginia Tech. 
</P>
<P>
 The Ventura College group, led by instructor Bill Hendricks, was only supposed 
to help the Virginia Tech students document the island's historic buildings. 
</P>
<P>
 But they came away with an idea for a project of their own: the Cubans 
themselves. 
</P>
<P>
 "The people were incredible," said M. Hughes Cary, one of the photography 
students who made the trip. "They are well-educated but have no place to use 
their education. Their economy is grinding to a halt, and their transportation 
is very primitive. But they cope with this with a lot of humor." 
</P>
<P>
 The show, titled "Cuba: Politics Aside," will open in Ventura College on Sept. 
6 and showcase the work of the amateur photographers throughout the month. 
</P>
<P>
 Most of the photos were shot in Havana, where the group spent most of their 
time, but some depict scenes from the rural Cienfuegos Province. 
</P>
<P>
 "It was a walking picture book," Ventura photographer Jennifer Selby said of 
the island. "Every different place had great things to shoot." 
</P>
<P>
 Cary said the conditions under which Cubans live -- chronic shortages of food 
and clothing, and a lack of common amenities like toilet seats -- was difficult 
to witness. 
</P>
<P>
 "This woman I met, she had three (bread) rolls in her right hand," he said. 
"And that was her ration for the day." 
</P>
<P>
 But the hope and optimism exhibited by the people made the most lasting 
impression on the visitors, who were allowed on the island with special 
research visas. 
</P>
<P>
 "They seemed to have very little," Selby said, "but they treated us like they 
had a lot." 
</P>
<P>
 A special reception for the exhibit will take place Sept. 6 at 7 p.m. For 
information, call Bill Hendricks at 654-6476 MIGUEL BUSTILLO 
</P>
</TEXT>
