<TEXT>
<P>
 China Details Copyright Crackdown: The government trumpeted the success of a 
recent clampdown on such violations, following pressure from the United States 
to improve protection of foreign intellectual property rights.In the first half 
of 1994, authorities seized about 5.94 million books and magazines that 
violated copyright laws or spread violence and pornography, the New China News 
Agency said. It did not specify how many were copyright violations. About 
200,000 pirated compact discs and 750,000 video- and audiotapes were also 
confiscated, it said. About 7,000 people were arrested and 56 factories and 
shops were closed. 
</P>
