<HEADLINE>
<P>
COMMUNITY NEWS: HARBOR AREA; REPORT ON IMPROVING TRUCK TRAFFIC APPROVED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By SUSAN WOODWARD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Harbor Commission has approved an environmental report on Port of Los 
Angeles plans to improve the flow of truck traffic through Wilmington. 
</P>
<P>
 The port is considering several ways to provide a truck route between the 
Harbor Freeway and Alameda Street.One option was criticized during a public 
hearing Friday.  
</P>
<P>
 Gwen Butterfield, secretary of the Wilmington North Neighborhood Assn., said a 
recommendation to build a 20-foot-high sound wall along C Street would close in 
the Wilmington community like a prison wall. 
</P>
<P>
 And outgoing Commissioner Gertrude Schwab, a longtime Wilmington activist, 
said the community option is to have a natural buffer with commercial 
development, not a wall. 
</P>
<P>
 She was the only commissioner to vote against the environmental report.  
</P>
<P>
 "We might as well put up barbed wire and machine guns on top and tell the 
community to stay out," Schwab said. The wall "will block the view of the port 
and stop airflow from coming into the community and only be an eyesore." SUSAN 
WOODWARD 
</P>
</TEXT>
